Contradict fact: The claim contradicts the fact that the new coronavirus is not the "least deadly virus" and actually has a higher death rate than the 2009 H1N1 outbreak.
Exaggerate: The claim exaggerates the low death rate of the new coronavirus and downplays its severity compared to other viruses.
Understate: The claim understates the actual death rate of the new coronavirus and fails to acknowledge that it is more fatal than the seasonal flu.
Lack enough support: The claim lacks enough support as it is based on outdated information and a misleading chart.
Problematic assumption: The claim makes the problematic assumption that the new coronavirus is the "least deadly virus" without considering the current data and expert opinions.
Exist alternative explanation: The claim does not consider alternative explanations for the death rate of the new coronavirus, such as the possibility of it being higher than currently estimated.
